The town is a quiet settlement on a natural harbour with a rich history of logging & gold mining.

The Coromandel peninsula is is cloaked in native forest & bordered by white sandy beaches making it an outdoor enthusiasts paradise. There are plenty of opportunities for fishing, diving, kayaking, walking & cycling or simply relaxing on a secluded beach. The region has a relaxed atmosphere & is home to many artists & craftspeople with local studios or galleries.

 

Things to See & Do:

* Boat cruise - to Cathedral Cove

* Kayak the beautiful coastline

* Walk the Coromandel Coastal Walkway

Auckland is New Zealand's largest city, with nearly one third of the country's population (1.4 million people). The range of activities in Auckland & the surrounding region is as diverse as the people; from shopping in top-end stores or open-air markets, dining in world class restaurants & cafes, exploring the stunning natural playground or soaking up the local culture, Auckland has something for everyone.

Known as the City of Sails, Auckland is located on an isthmus that separates two harbours: Waitemata Harbour to the north and Manukau Harbour to the south. Over 3,000 kilometres of coastline, plus several nearby islands make water activities popular with both locals & visitors.

 Things to see & do:

Arthur's Pass is nestled amongst the Southern Alps in the South Island

Climbing to more than 900 metres through Arthur's Pass National Park, is the highest and most spectacular pass across the Southern Alps.  Arthur’s Pass National Park itself is a landscape of two halves. On the eastern side see wide, shingle-filled riverbeds and vast swathes of beech forest. Descend the western side and venture through dense rainforest and over deeply gorged rivers.

Things to See & Do

  • Hike around this region
  • Ski or Snowboard in Winter in the Temple Basin Ski Area
  • Devils Punchbowl Waterfall

Arrow Junction is located approximately 17 kilometres from Central Queenstown.

On the shores of Lake Wakatipu & surrounded by alpine ranges, Queenstown has the perfect mix of beauty, adventure & relaxation.

Queenstown is undoubtedly the adventure capital of New Zealand offering year-round activities such as jet boating, white water rafting, bungy jumping, canyon swinging & sky diving. Winter then brings the added bonus of world-class skiing.

If you prefer a more relaxed holiday, the stunning scenery can be enjoyed from the gondola or a boat cruise on the lake. The surrounding region also features in The Lord of the Rings trilogy & tours can be taken of the many filming locations.

 

Things to See & Do:

* Get the a adrenaline pumping with jet boating, white water rafting, bungy jumping, canyon swinging or sky diving

* Cruise Lake Wakatipu on the paddlesteamer the Earnslaw

* Explore some of the many walking tracks

* Take a Lord of the Rings Tour

Waitomo Caves are a maze of underground rivers with limestone walls covered in glowworms. The caves can be viewed by boat on a guided tour or the more adventurous can try blackwater rafting - crawling, swimming & floating through the caves on a rubber tube.

If you'd rather stay above ground, there is a museum, cafe & beautiful nature walks to enjoy.  

Things to see & do:

  • Guided walking or boat tour of the caves
  • Blackwater rafting
  • Nature walks

If you prefer a more relaxed holiday, the stunning scenery can be enjoyed from the gondola or a boat cruise on the lake. The surrounding region also features in The Lord of the Rings trilogy & tours can be taken of the many filming locations.

Things to see & do:

  • Take a Lord of the Rings Tour

Millbrook Resort, Arrowtown is located 19 kilometres from Central Queenstown.

Arrowtown is a picturesque historic town; settled in the gold rush of the mid 1800's, the town still has a quaint feel with many of the original building restored as shops, cafe's & restaurants.

 

Queenstown is undoubtedly the adventure capital of New Zealand offering year-round activities such as jet boating, white water rafting, bungy jumping, canyon swinging & sky diving. Winter then brings the added bonus of world-class skiing.

If you prefer a more relaxed holiday, the stunning scenery can be enjoyed from the gondola or a boat cruise on the lake. The surrounding region also features in The Lord of the Rings trilogy & tours can be taken of the many filming locations.

 

Things to See & Do:

* Get the a adrenaline pumping with jet boating, white water rafting, bungy jumping, canyon swinging or sky diving

* Cruise Lake Wakatipu on the paddlesteamer the Earnslaw

* Explore some of the many walking tracks

* Take a Lord of the Rings Tour

Milford Sound is located on the West Coast of the South Island.

Milford Sound is the most assessable fiord in New Zealand. The 16 kilometres from the head of the fiord to the open sea is bounded by rocky shores, dense rainforest & steep cliffs. The magestic Mitre Peak rises 1692 metres from sea level to it's tip.

The small village has a cafe & tavern, but only a handful of places to stay.

Things to see & do:

  • Scenic Boat Cruise is an absolute must!
  • Seakayaking & diving are available for the adventurous

Wellington is not only the capital of New Zealand, but also the arts, culture & culinary capital as well with hundreds of theatres, art galleries & museums including the national museum - Te Papa. Wellingtonians are passionate about good food, with more restaurants & bars per capita than New York City.

Wellington also has a thriving movie industry & is also home to Weta Workshop - a must for any Lord of the Rings fan.

Manukau is located approximately 10 kilometres from Auckland International Airport and 24 kilometres from Downtown Auckland.

Auckland is New Zealand's largest city, with nearly one third of the country's population (1.4 million people). The range of activities in Auckland & the surrounding region is nearly as diverse as the number of people; from shopping in top-end stores or open-air markets, dining in world class restaurants & cafes, exploring the stunning natural playground or soaking up the local culture, Auckland has something for everyone.

Known as the City of Sails, Auckland is located on an isthmus that separates two harbours: Waitemata Harbour to the north and Manukau Harbour to the south. Over 3,000 kilometres of coastline, plus several nearby islands make water activities popular with both locals & visitors.

Things to see & do:

  • Shop & dine in downtown hot spots - Viaduct Harbour, Wynyard Quarter or Britomart Precinct
  • Enjoy nature walks or mountain biking in one of several regional parks
  • Visit the nearby islands - Waiheke, Rangitoto, Great Barrier
  • Explore rugged West Coast beaches

Nelson is located at the top of the South Island

Being one of the sunniest cities in New Zealand & a laid-back atmosphere makes Nelson an ideal place to rest & recharge the batteries. Local & international art can be viewed in the many markets, studios, galleries & museums. Nelson is also the gateway to the Abel Tasman & Kahurangi National Parks.

 

Things to See & Do:

* World of Wearable Art And Classic Car Museum

* Meet local craftspeople at the market or studios

* Explore the many boutique wineries of the region

At the heart of Nuhaka is the Kahungunu Marae, beautifully built & carved by WWII veterans in the 1940s. There are eight marae serving Nuhaka & the surrounding communities.

Things to see & do:

  • Visis Kahungunu Marae
  • Hunting & Fishing in Te Uruwera National Park

Northlands Mall is located aproximately 5 kilometres from central Christchurch.

 

Christchurch City offers an eclectic mix of historic & contemporary culture as it rebuilds & recovers from the earthquakes of 2010 & 2011.

In true Kiwi style, the locals have come up with innovative ways to make the most of the changes including a shipping container mall, outdoor markets, temporary Cardboard Cathedral & pop-up resaurants & bars.

Known as the Garden City, the city's Botanic Gardens are over 150 years old and boasts a huge collection of native & exotic plants.   

 

Things to see & do:

* Re-Start Mall

* Botanic Gardens

* Punting on the Avon River

* International Antarctic Centre

Napier is located in Hawkes Bay, on the East Coast of the North Island.

Hawkes Bay is the Art Deco capital of New Zealand after the region was devastated by an earthquake in the 1930s & rebuilt in the style of the day. This heritage is celebrated with the Art Deco weekend held in February every year.

Hawkes Bay is also known for it's range of local produce & wineries. 

Things to see & do:

  • Take a guided walk of the city centre
  • Visit the regions many wineries
  • Visit Cape Kidnappers Gannet Colony

Otorohanga is located in Waikato, approximately 60 kilometres from Hamilton.

Otorohanga is the self-titled Kiwiana Capital, the town walls are painted with New Zealand icons.

Nearby Waitomo Caves have a maze of underground rivers with limestone walls covered in glowworms. The caves can be viewed by boat on a guided tour or the more adventurous can try blackwater rafting - crawling, swimming & floating through the caves on a rubber tube.

Things to see & do:

  • See Kiwi in their native habitat at Kiwi House
  • Explore Waitomo Caves

Okarito Turn Off is located 5 kilometres from Franz Josef Village on the West Coast of the South Island, Okarito is another 13 kilometres from this turn off.

Okarito is a bird watchers paradise with a huge variety of coastal birdlife in New Zealand's largest estuarine lagoon, including a White Heron (Kotuku) colony.

While the glaciers are the main attractions in the region, there are many other natural & historic attractions.

 

Things to See & Do:

* View the birdlife of the Okarito Lagoon

* Explore the former gold town

 

Nearby:

* Guided walks to get up close to the glaciers

* Scenic flight to view the glaciers

* Lake Matheson - mirror lake reflecting the Southern Alps

Orewa is located 37 kilometres north of Downtown Auckland.

 

Auckland is New Zealand's largest city, with nearly one third of the country's population (1.4 million people). The range of activities in Auckland & the surrounding region is nearly as diverse as the number of people; from shopping in top-end stores or open-air markets, dining in world class restaurants & cafes, exploring the stunning natural playground or soaking up the local culture, Auckland has something for everyone.

Known as the City of Sails, Auckland is located on an isthmus that separates two harbours: Waitemata Harbour to the north and Manukau Harbour to the south. Over 3,000 kilometres of coastline, plus several nearby islands make water activities popular with both locals & visitors.

 

Things to see & do:

* Shop & dine in downtown hot spots - Viaduct Harbour, Wynyard Quarter or Britomart Precinct

* Enjoy nature walks or mountain biking in one of several regional parks

* Visit the nearby islands - Waiheke, Rangitoto, Great Barrier

* Explore rugged West Coast beaches

column9:
Punakaiki is located on the West Coast of the South Island.

The main drawcard of Punakaiki is the natural phenomenon known at the """"Pancake Rocks"""" - layered rocks eroded over thousands of years. At high tide, the pounding waves create geyser-like blowholes shooting water high into the air. A well-maintained track leads visitors to the best views while keeping a safe distance from the perilous cliffs.

The local area also offers a range of other activites including rafting, caving & horse trekking.

Things to see & do:

  • Explore the """"Pancake Rocks""""
  • Rafting, caving & horse trekking

The Coromandel peninsula is is cloaked in native forest & bordered by white sandy beaches making it an outdoor enthusiasts paradise. There are plenty of opportunities for fishing, diving, kayaking, walking & cycling or simply relaxing on a secluded beach. The region has a relaxed atmosphere & is home to many artists & craftspeople with local studios or galleries.

Things to See & Do:

  • Kayak the beautiful coastline
  • Walk the Coromandel Coastal Walkway
  • Take a photo with the iconic giant L&P Bottle

Riccarton Road is located aproximately 5 kilometres from central Christchurch.

 

Christchurch City offers an eclectic mix of historic & contemporary culture as it rebuilds & recovers from the earthquakes of 2010 & 2011.

In true Kiwi style, the locals have come up with innovative ways to make the most of the changes including a shipping container mall, outdoor markets, temporary Cardboard Cathedral & pop-up resaurants & bars.

Known as the Garden City, the city's Botanic Gardens are over 150 years old and boasts a huge collection of native & exotic plants.   

 

Things to see & do:

* Re-Start Mall

* Botanic Gardens

* Punting on the Avon River

* International Antarctic Centre

Rakaia is located in Canterbury, approximately 57 kilometres from Christchurch.

Near the banks of the Rakaia River, fishing, kayaking & jet boating are popular activities in this small town.  The longest road bridge & the longest rail bridge cross the Rakaia River just north of the town.

Things to see & do:

  • Salmon World
  • Fishing

Rotorua is located in the Bay of Plenty, in the North Island.

The Tourism Mecca of Rotorua offers the perfect mix of adventure & relaxation. After a day of mountain biking, horse riding, bungy jumping, white water rafting, luging or ziplining you can unwind in natural hot springs. Rotorua is a geothermal wonderland with bubbling mud pools & explosive geysers.

Rotorua also offers a Maori culture experience, combining warm hospitality with singing, dancing & traditional food.

Things to see & do:

  • Wai-o-Tapu Thermal Wonderland
  • Whakarewarewa Thermal Village
  • Skyline Rotorua - Gondola, Luge & Zip-lining
  • Tamaki Maori Village

Roxburgh is located in Central Otago, half way between Dunedin & Queenstown.

This historic gold-mining town is now best known for it's summer fruit, hydro dam, lake & walking trails. The Lake Roxburgh Walk contains many interesting relics from gold-mining days including huts, shelters & various mine workings. The lake also offers excellent kayaking & fishing.

Things to see & do:

  • Hiking & mountain biking
  • Visit historic sites
  • Kayaking
  • Trout fishing

Wellington also has a thriving movie industry & is also home to Weta Workshop - a must for any Lord of the Rings fan.

Whanganui is located in the central North Island

Whanganui is one of New Zealand oldest settler towns and its history is on display everywhere - from its prominent hertage buildings to the paddlesteamer cruising the river.

The city has a vibrant arts & culture scene, and it's proximity to mountains, national parks & rivers makes it an interestingly diverse city with something for everyone.

Things to see & do:

  • Explore Whanganui River - by steamer, kayak or jetboat
  • Visit Whanganui National Park & the Bridge to Nowhere
  • Visit some of the many galleries & artist studios

Waitomo Caves are located in Waikato, approximately 74 kilometres from Hamilton.

Waitomo Caves are a maze of underground rivers with limestone walls covered in glowworms. The caves can be viewed by boat on a guided tour or the more adventurous can try blackwater rafting - crawling, swimming & floating through the caves on a rubber tube.

If you'd rather stay above ground, there is a museum, cafe & beautiful nature walks to enjoy.  

Things to see & do:

  • Guided walking or boat tour of the caves
  • Blackwater rafting
  • Nature walks

Auckland is New Zealand's largest city, with nearly one third of the country's population (1.4 million people). The range of activities in Auckland & the surrounding region is nearly as diverse as the number of people; from shopping in top-end stores or open-air markets, dining in world class restaurants & cafes, exploring the stunning natural playground or soaking up the local culture, Auckland has something for everyone.

Known as the City of Sails, Auckland is located on an isthmus that separates two harbours: Waitemata Harbour to the north and Manukau Harbour to the south. Over 3,000 kilometres of coastline, plus several nearby islands make water activities popular with both locals & visitors.

 

Things to see & do:

* Shop & dine in downtown hot spots - Viaduct Harbour, Wynyard Quarter or Britomart Precinct

* Enjoy nature walks or mountain biking in one of several regional parks

* Visit the nearby islands - Waiheke, Rangitoto, Great Barrier

* Explore rugged West Coast beaches

column9:
Queenstown YHA is located in Central Queenstown.

On the shores of Lake Wakatipu & surrounded by alpine ranges, Queenstown has the perfect mix of beauty, adventure & relaxation.

Queenstown is undoubtedly the adventure capital of New Zealand offering year-round activities such as jet boating, white water rafting, bungy jumping, canyon swinging & sky diving. Winter then brings the added bonus of world-class skiing.

If you prefer a more relaxed holiday, the stunning scenery can be enjoyed from the gondola or a boat cruise on the lake. The surrounding region also features in The Lord of the Rings trilogy & tours can be taken of the many filming locations.

 

Things to See & Do:

* Get the a adrenaline pumping with jet boating, white water rafting, bungy jumping, canyon swinging or sky diving

* Cruise Lake Wakatipu on the paddlesteamer the Earnslaw

* Explore some of the many walking tracks

* Take a Lord of the Rings Tour

column9:
Arthur's Pass is nestled amongst the Southern Alps in the South Island

Climbing to more than 900 metres through Arthur's Pass National Park, is the highest and most spectacular pass across the Southern Alps.  Arthur’s Pass National Park itself is a landscape of two halves. On the eastern side see wide, shingle-filled riverbeds and vast swathes of beech forest. Descend the western side and venture through dense rainforest and over deeply gorged rivers.

Things to See & Do

  • Hike around this region
  • Ski or Snowboard in Winter in the Temple Basin Ski Area
  • Devils Punchbowl Waterfall

Things to see & do:

  • Te Papa - national museum
  • Weta Workshop
  • Wellington Cable Car & Botanic Gardens
  • Visit quirky cafes & award-winning restaurants in Cuba St & Courtenay Place

column9:
Auckland Central - Sky City Hotel is located in the heart of downtown Auckland, approximately 20 kilometres from Auckland International Aiport.

Auckland is New Zealand's largest city, with nearly one third of the country's population (1.4 million people). The range of activities in Auckland & the surrounding region is nearly as diverse as the number of people; from shopping in top-end stores or open-air markets, dining in world class restaurants & cafes, exploring the stunning natural playground or soaking up the local culture, Auckland has something for everyone.

Known as the City of Sails, Auckland is located on an isthmus that separates two harbours: Waitemata Harbour to the north and Manukau Harbour to the south. Over 3,000 kilometres of coastline, plus several nearby islands make water activities popular with both locals & visitors.

Things to see & do:

  • Shop & dine in downtown hot spots - Viaduct Harbour, Wynyard Quarter or Britomart Precinct
  • Enjoy nature walks or mountain biking in one of several regional parks
  • Visit the nearby islands - Waiheke, Rangitoto, Great Barrier
  • Explore rugged West Coast beaches

Invercargill is New Zealand's Southernmost city, located at the bottom of the South Island.

The charming city features wide streets, Victorian, Edwardian & Art Deco architecture.

Things to see & do:

  • Visit Queens Park rose gardens
  • Explore Southland Museum & Art Gallery
  • Take a trip to the Southernmost point of New Zealand's mainland at Bluff
